descript.abstract: This point dataset shows the locations for all named places in New Hampshire according to the federal Geographic Names Information System (GNIS) as of 2008. Place name locations from the federal GNIS have been corrected and updated, based upon a variety of sources, including current and historic US Geological Survey topographic maps, aerial photography, New Hampshire state agency records, and current web sites. This data set will provide a quick reference for anyone wishing to determine what features in New Hampshire have names. It will also aid those wishing to name an unnamed feature in New Hampshire, by indicating whether duplicate or similar names exist elsewhere in the state.
descript.purpose: This dataset is intended for researchers, students, and policy makers for reference and mapping purposes, and may be used for basic applications such as viewing, querying, and map output production, or to provide a basemap to support graphical overlays and analysis with other spatial data.

attracc.attraccr: Attribute information remains the same as given by the author of the data. However, when information is missing or ambiguous, the GIS Information Systems Center at Tufts University researches other metadata sources for explanations. If sufficient information is unavailable, "unknown attribute" is given as the definition. If the attribute has been created through a geoprocessing function, "geoprocessed identifier" is given. If the attribute is known, but the values are not, "unknown" is given for values. Features' units of measurement are determined if not already given.

qattracc.attracce: Feature names are derived directly from federal Geographic Names Information System. Some editing has been performed by the NH Office of Energy and Planning (see individual attribute values). Occasional, obvious errors in feature names (e.g. Ammonoosucuc for Ammonoosuc) have been corrected, but otherwise all names are assumed to be correct as stored.
Source values were found, upon editing, to be frequently (5%) inaccurate and have been corrected to the Office of Energy and Planning's best judgement.
100% accurate (all values are for New Hampshire).
99% accurate. Some quadrangle names have not been updated to reflect corrected locations of some named features.

horizpa.horizpar: Original GNIS locations appeared to be derived from printed latitude/longitude pairs and contained numerous inaccuracies. All locations whose names appear on USGS quadrangles have been correctly located. Features such as churches, schools, and other structures are estimated to be 80% accurate.

srcinfo.srccontr: 95% of feature locations were tied to the USGS DRGs.

procstep.procdesc: Dataset copied from Geographic Names Information System web site. Tabular data contained latitude and longitude pairs for each feature. ArcInfo Generate command created an ArcInfo coverage, which was then converted, using ArcGIS 9.1, into geodatabase format. Features were displayed using USGS Digital Raster Graphics backdrop, and feature locations were adjusted to match the DRGS. Where the feature was not visible on the DRG, 2003 NAIP photography was used, along with information culled from historic USGS quadrangles dating back to 1900, and with current information from features' web sites. Upon completion of editing, dataset was projected into NH State Plane coordinates and converted to shapefile format.

procstep.procdesc: Complex Systems Research Center acquired shapefile from NH Office of Energy and Planning. In comparing tabular data to spatial data, nine hundred and twenty-four tabular records were found to have missing spatial locations. These records were removed from the data, and the shapefile was provided back to NH Office of Energy and Planning.

attr.attrdef: Type of named feature: Derived from GNIS "feature class". A feature class is a designation for a group of features in a broadly defined descriptive category. All features are assigned to one and only one class. They do not individually classify all kinds of cultural and natural features. By design, there are no Federal or industry standards or guidelines for feature classification. These classifications originally were developed for mainframe file structure search purposes. Although the terms are generally consistent with dictionary definitions, they may not conform exactly and are not always intuitive.
